256
00:22:02.713 --> 00:22:04.505
I'm the lawyer.

257
00:22:04.599 --> 00:22:06.810
[protesters continue shouting]

258
00:22:08.309 --> 00:22:10.103
<i>[bell ringing]</i>

259
00:22:24.117 --> 00:22:26.119
Fifth Circuit's gonna rule against us.

260
00:22:28.571 --> 00:22:31.114
I'm sorry. Leanne.

261
00:22:31.249 --> 00:22:33.272
[sighs] The governor is a long shot.

262
00:22:33.376 --> 00:22:35.327
- LEANNE: You know?
- But...

263
00:22:35.967 --> 00:22:39.975
I grew up downwind
from a cereal factory.

264
00:22:40.675 --> 00:22:42.635
A mile from home.

265
00:22:43.636 --> 00:22:46.055
Smelled like Cheerios.

266
00:22:47.348 --> 00:22:49.183
That was my first memory.

267
00:22:52.061 --> 00:22:53.604
What's yours?

268
00:22:54.793 --> 00:22:57.754
- What?
- Your first memory.

269
00:23:00.877 --> 00:23:03.478
[Gene Pitney] <i>♪ I was only ♪</i>

270
00:23:03.546 --> 00:23:06.991
<i>♪ 24 hours from Tulsa ♪</i>

271
00:23:07.049 --> 00:23:08.676
<i>[car door slams]</i>

272
00:23:09.719 --> 00:23:11.429
Gene Pitney.

273
00:23:11.596 --> 00:23:13.723
"24 Hours from Tulsa."

274
00:23:18.102 --> 00:23:20.252
That's a nice song.

275
00:23:20.354 --> 00:23:22.315
"24 Hours from Tulsa."

276
00:23:23.316 --> 00:23:25.241
My dad...

277
00:23:25.318 --> 00:23:27.110
used to take me to a honky-tonk place

278
00:23:27.111 --> 00:23:29.112
on the south side of Dallas.

279
00:23:29.113 --> 00:23:31.114
He'd get good and drunk and take me

280
00:23:31.115 --> 00:23:33.450
to the alligator farm just next door.

281
00:23:33.576 --> 00:23:36.606
We'd sit there and stare
at those gators for two.

282
00:23:36.661 --> 00:23:38.746
three hours at a time.

283
00:23:38.873 --> 00:23:41.208
Sometimes I'd get to drive the car home

284
00:23:41.209 --> 00:23:42.543
at the end of the night.

285
00:23:45.171 --> 00:23:47.342
What I keep wondering.

286
00:23:47.632 --> 00:23:49.549
all the smells we smell

287
00:23:50.131 --> 00:23:53.389
and the... songs and pictures...

288
00:23:53.930 --> 00:23:55.680
do you lose them all?

289
00:23:56.265 --> 00:23:57.399
I mean.

290
00:23:57.558 --> 00:23:59.719
wherever you go next.

291
00:24:00.019 --> 00:24:01.811
does the tape get erased?

292
00:24:02.172 --> 00:24:04.345
And if it does...

293
00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:08.444
you're not really you anymore. are ya?

294
00:24:11.739 --> 00:24:13.908
Is that what you're afraid of?

295
00:24:16.410 --> 00:24:18.746
That's what I want.

296
00:24:21.415 --> 00:24:23.834
<i>♪♪</i>

297
00:24:27.338 --> 00:24:28.972
MAN: <i>Look at me.</i>

298
00:24:29.034 --> 00:24:32.259
Look at me. I'm Alan.
I'm a friend of your mother's.

299
00:24:32.260 --> 00:24:33.969
["24 Hours from Tulsa"
playing on car radio]

300
00:24:33.970 --> 00:24:36.136
No frostbite.

301
00:24:36.264 --> 00:24:37.848
You been inside somewhere?

302
00:24:55.992 --> 00:24:57.702
[monitor beeping]

303
00:25:08.671 --> 00:25:11.674
[beeping slows]

304
00:25:15.594 --> 00:25:18.222
[beeping fades]

305
00:25:25.730 --> 00:25:27.356
[man. indistinct]

306
00:25:31.444 --> 00:25:34.336
[alarm wails]

307
00:25:34.383 --> 00:25:36.699
- What's goin' on?
- She's alive again!

308
00:25:37.546 --> 00:25:38.630
HENRY: What...

309
00:25:40.494 --> 00:25:42.119
- Hey!
- [beeping. alarm wailing]

310
00:25:42.305 --> 00:25:43.673
Hey. I'm her witness.

311
00:25:43.789 --> 00:25:45.749
You don't get a fucking do-over!

312
00:25:45.750 --> 00:25:48.210
[shouting. indistinct]

313
00:25:49.855 --> 00:25:51.338
...fuckin' witness!

314
00:25:51.455 --> 00:25:53.132
- [alarm continues]
- Hey!

315
00:26:03.017 --> 00:26:04.477
[tires squeal]

316
00:26:13.319 --> 00:26:15.196
[car departs]

317
00:26:17.374 --> 00:26:19.334
MAN: <i>Henry Matthew Deaver.</i>

318
00:26:19.583 --> 00:26:22.660
Based out of Houston.
grew up 20 miles that way.

319
00:26:22.731 --> 00:26:24.075
Castle Rock.

320
00:26:24.163 --> 00:26:25.802
Bad reputation.

321
00:26:25.915 --> 00:26:28.166
Big mess with the state police
when he was a kid.

322
00:26:28.728 --> 00:26:32.017
<i>Pulled some stunt. ran away from home.</i>

323
00:26:32.171 --> 00:26:34.470
<i>People thought somebody took him.</i>

324
00:26:34.632 --> 00:26:36.508
<i>Half the state's out looking for him.</i>

325
00:26:36.509 --> 00:26:37.900
<i>Middle of winter.</i>

326
00:26:38.010 --> 00:26:40.307
<i>And what they find is his father.</i>

327
00:26:40.429 --> 00:26:43.010
<i>Half-froze. and his back's broken.</i>

328
00:26:43.185 --> 00:26:45.706
<i>Doesn't last three days.</i>

329
00:26:46.519 --> 00:26:49.229
<i>Kid comes sashaying back
from the dead like Tom Sawyer</i>

330
00:26:49.230 --> 00:26:53.347
<i>to find out he's got no dad.
and the town blames him.</i>

331
00:26:53.717 --> 00:26:56.302
<i>Claimed he couldn't remember a thing.</i>

332
00:26:56.570 --> 00:26:58.860
WARDEN: So. our anonymous friend
says exactly three words.

333
00:26:58.948 --> 00:27:01.367
and we think that he's asking
for his lawyer?

334
00:27:03.762 --> 00:27:06.720
I think we are not bringing
a criminal defense attorney

335
00:27:06.790 --> 00:27:09.477
into an internal
corporate matter. Mnh-mnh.

336
00:27:09.542 --> 00:27:12.118
We could take him for a drive.
Drop him over the border.

337
00:27:12.169 --> 00:27:13.360
Yeah. then he pulls a Willie Horton

338
00:27:13.385 --> 00:27:14.712
and I spend the rest of my career

339
00:27:14.713 --> 00:27:15.840
in accounts receivable.

340
00:27:20.302 --> 00:27:22.137
Or we could find him a roomie.

341
00:27:22.459 --> 00:27:26.287
A psycho who collects
life sentences. Circle of life.

342
00:27:31.564 --> 00:27:32.773
[chicken clucking]

343
00:27:37.987 --> 00:27:40.114
[chicken squawking]

344
00:27:47.204 --> 00:27:49.665
[wings clank against fence]

345
00:27:53.502 --> 00:27:55.045
[hissing]

346
00:28:04.889 --> 00:28:06.765
- [squawking]
- [alligator hissing]

347
00:28:12.188 --> 00:28:14.064
[cellphone chiming]

348
00:28:17.036 --> 00:28:18.662
Hello?

349
00:28:20.473 --> 00:28:21.931
Yeah.

350
00:28:22.025 --> 00:28:24.033
Yeah. Henry Matthew Deaver the attorney.

351
00:28:26.535 --> 00:28:28.453
What? I-I can't hear you.

352
00:28:28.454 --> 00:28:30.623
<i>[man talking. indistinct]</i>

353
00:28:32.750 --> 00:28:34.260
Whoever you've got isn't my client.

354
00:28:34.330 --> 00:28:35.767
My clients are all dead.

355
00:28:35.836 --> 00:28:37.450
Look. I shouldn't even be calling you.

356
00:28:37.493 --> 00:28:40.239
but listen. listen.
they found a kid in a cage.

357
00:28:42.718 --> 00:28:44.390
No one else is gonna help him.

358
00:28:44.470 --> 00:28:46.096
Shawshank State Prison.

359
00:28:47.556 --> 00:28:49.307
[crowing]

360
00:28:49.308 --> 00:28:50.851
Who... Who is this?

361
00:29:00.319 --> 00:29:03.030
<i>♪♪</i>

362
00:29:23.842 --> 00:29:26.804
<i>[rock music playing on car radio]</i>

363
00:29:32.518 --> 00:29:34.235
BOY: The MILF.

364
00:29:35.342 --> 00:29:37.343
Twice in one month?

365
00:29:37.439 --> 00:29:40.659
If I find out you've been...
subcontracting me...

366
00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:43.437
What? You'll tell your homeroom teacher?

367
00:29:45.239 --> 00:29:48.575
It's for me. I've got a condition.

368
00:29:51.412 --> 00:29:54.012
Oh. yeah. I can get you rest
on Thursday or...

369
00:29:54.081 --> 00:29:55.551
a postdated check if you want.

370
00:29:55.624 --> 00:29:58.252
Obamacare's been repealed. No co-pays.

371
00:29:59.378 --> 00:30:00.921
Forty gets you eight fives.

372
00:30:05.259 --> 00:30:08.546
- You need kids. by the way.
- What?

373
00:30:08.762 --> 00:30:11.054
- To be a MILF.
- [laughs]

374
00:30:13.196 --> 00:30:14.614
See you around.

375
00:30:23.402 --> 00:30:25.404
[rock music blaring]

376
00:30:42.209 --> 00:30:43.794
DRIVER: Here you go.

377
00:30:47.009 --> 00:30:48.510
[distant chatter]

378
00:31:14.627 --> 00:31:17.003
RADIO: <i>...by the power that is our Lord.</i>

379
00:31:17.090 --> 00:31:19.134
[sermon continues on radio]

380
00:31:43.107 --> 00:31:45.109
<i>♪♪</i>

381
00:31:59.706 --> 00:32:01.583
[indistinct shouting]

382
00:32:07.089 --> 00:32:08.424
Hey. killer.

383
00:32:31.039 --> 00:32:32.916
HENRY: What the hell?

384
00:32:34.587 --> 00:32:35.922
[thud]

385
00:32:45.002 --> 00:32:47.713
[man speaking in distance]

386
00:32:49.826 --> 00:32:53.387
MAN: <i>...9-12 says.
"But two are better than one.</i>

387
00:32:53.564 --> 00:32:57.109
<i>"because they have
a good return on their labor.</i>

388
00:32:57.219 --> 00:32:59.261
<i>If either of them falls down.</i>

389
00:32:59.349 --> 00:33:02.402
<i>one can help the other up.</i>

390
00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:05.500
<i>But pity anyone who falls..."</i>

391
00:33:05.649 --> 00:33:07.109
ALAN: <i>It was minus-forty last night.</i>

392
00:33:09.429 --> 00:33:10.888
You know how cold that is?

393
00:33:12.677 --> 00:33:14.929
Freeze to death in an hour.

394
00:33:15.032 --> 00:33:17.784
And you've been gone. like. 11 days.

395
00:33:20.412 --> 00:33:22.080
So what happened out there?

396
00:33:26.768 --> 00:33:28.353
I don't remember.

397
00:33:29.379 --> 00:33:31.422
[sighs]

398
00:33:31.447 --> 00:33:34.325
Son. do you know what happened
to your father?

399
00:33:40.011 --> 00:33:41.310
Okay.

400
00:33:45.395 --> 00:33:46.688
[slams]

401
00:34:02.412 --> 00:34:04.998
<i>♪♪</i>

402
00:34:14.216 --> 00:34:15.884
[crying]

403
00:34:18.480 --> 00:34:19.856
Henry!

404
00:34:33.485 --> 00:34:35.904
[fire alarm beeping]

405
00:34:36.769 --> 00:34:38.020
Hello?

406
00:34:41.508 --> 00:34:43.343
[TV playing]

407
00:34:43.383 --> 00:34:44.841
HENRY: Mom?

408
00:34:44.881 --> 00:34:47.299
- [fire alarm sounding]
- [hissing]

409
00:34:47.394 --> 00:34:49.188
[groans]

410
00:34:53.672 --> 00:34:55.799
[alarm continues]

411
00:35:06.768 --> 00:35:08.437
HENRY: Mom?

412
00:35:09.521 --> 00:35:11.106
Ruth?

413
00:35:12.107 --> 00:35:14.672
Oh! My. uh...

414
00:35:14.735 --> 00:35:16.778
my white oaks are dead.

415
00:35:18.590 --> 00:35:20.215
It's a miracle they didn't topple over

416
00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:21.767
and kill someone.

417
00:35:21.825 --> 00:35:24.290
Did you bring your own chainsaw?

418
00:35:24.375 --> 00:35:27.664
Well. then. let's check the garage.

419
00:35:28.610 --> 00:35:31.863
Come on now!
We were all immigrants once.

420
00:35:31.919 --> 00:35:34.292
Except Sitting Bull. [laughs]

421
00:35:34.337 --> 00:35:36.379
I'm not like the others.

422
00:35:36.506 --> 00:35:40.073
- I adopted a black son.
- Mom. Mom.

423
00:35:40.593 --> 00:35:43.678
It's me. I'm Henry.

424
00:35:43.805 --> 00:35:45.641
I called you this morning.

425
00:35:47.726 --> 00:35:49.411
Henry.

426
00:35:49.522 --> 00:35:51.357
Yeah. of course you are.

427
00:35:52.397 --> 00:35:53.857
Okay.

428
00:36:05.994 --> 00:36:07.995
I had to fly in for a...

429
00:36:08.045 --> 00:36:09.733
a work thing.

430
00:36:09.831 --> 00:36:12.186
But I wanted to see you.

431
00:36:12.459 --> 00:36:14.522
Maris watching the baby?

432
00:36:14.753 --> 00:36:16.797
Wendell is fifteen. Mom.

433
00:36:19.437 --> 00:36:20.687
What...

434
00:36:20.759 --> 00:36:22.501
W-What happened to the nurse?

435
00:36:22.556 --> 00:36:24.529
- Who?
- Your Medicare pays

436
00:36:24.554 --> 00:36:25.743
for a home health aide.

437
00:36:25.768 --> 00:36:27.970
I arranged it all with St. Jude's.

438
00:36:28.936 --> 00:36:32.189
Oh! Constance. Long gone.

439
00:36:32.296 --> 00:36:34.009
Gone? Where?

440
00:36:34.071 --> 00:36:38.035
Well. I'd like to say heaven.
but I have my suspicions.

441
00:36:38.068 --> 00:36:39.611
[thudding]

442
00:36:40.779 --> 00:36:42.322
Is someone in the house?

443
00:36:43.615 --> 00:36:45.158
Someone's in the house?

444
00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:49.162
- [thudding]
- [TV playing]

445
00:36:50.372 --> 00:36:53.086
ALAN: Are we on fire?

446
00:36:53.220 --> 00:36:57.109
You know. there's easier ways
to get a man out of the shower.

447
00:37:00.786 --> 00:37:03.371
Henry. do you know Alan Pangborn?

448
00:37:03.427 --> 00:37:06.148
He's our county sheriff.

449
00:37:06.513 --> 00:37:07.835
Was.

450
00:37:08.140 --> 00:37:10.892
- Been a few years now. Ruth.
- Alan?

451
00:37:12.210 --> 00:37:14.378
W-What's going on?

452
00:37:14.521 --> 00:37:17.189
You boys must be hungry.
How about some bacon and eggs?

453
00:37:17.190 --> 00:37:18.983
Why don't you see if you can scare up

454
00:37:18.984 --> 00:37:21.342
some fresh sheets for your boy?

455
00:37:21.445 --> 00:37:23.272
- If he's stayin'.
- RUTH: Yeah.

456
00:37:23.772 --> 00:37:25.449
Few days.

457
00:37:26.908 --> 00:37:28.967
What brings you home?

458
00:37:29.220 --> 00:37:32.401
- A client.
- Oh. yeah?

459
00:37:32.460 --> 00:37:35.003
You've burned through
all the killers in Texas?

460
00:37:35.542 --> 00:37:38.737
So. what is this. Alan? You livin' here?

461
00:37:38.920 --> 00:37:41.175
Frequent flyer.

462
00:37:41.381 --> 00:37:45.196
Your mother and I enjoy
one another's companionship.

463
00:37:45.385 --> 00:37:47.876
And my father's shirts. you...

464
00:37:48.013 --> 00:37:50.024
enjoy those. too?

465
00:37:50.140 --> 00:37:52.212
I don't think he's gonna miss it.

466
00:37:52.309 --> 00:37:53.652
Where is he?

467
00:37:53.935 --> 00:37:56.198
- Who?
- My father.

468
00:37:56.772 --> 00:37:58.481
- Oh...
- I stopped by the church.

469
00:37:58.482 --> 00:38:00.534
and the cemetery is... is gone.

470
00:38:00.585 --> 00:38:03.170
Yeah. the church made
some wildcat investments.

471
00:38:03.195 --> 00:38:05.797
didn't pan out. had to parcel the land.

472
00:38:05.868 --> 00:38:07.703
So they... just...

473
00:38:07.783 --> 00:38:09.328
paved over the bodies?

474
00:38:09.383 --> 00:38:10.930
No. they moved 'em.

475
00:38:11.023 --> 00:38:14.900
To a yard up in Banner. by the airport.

476
00:38:14.956 --> 00:38:18.834
My experience.
the dead are not particular.

477
00:38:18.888 --> 00:38:20.795
They can't do
that without our permission.

478
00:38:20.841 --> 00:38:23.006
- You mother gave it.
- [scoffs]

479
00:38:26.301 --> 00:38:28.219
Nobody thought to pick up
the phone and call me?

480
00:38:28.293 --> 00:38:30.222
Did she even know
what she was signing for?

481
00:38:32.651 --> 00:38:34.193
You signed for her.

482
00:38:34.254 --> 00:38:37.229
I deposited the distress
settlement for her. too.

483
00:38:39.231 --> 00:38:41.107
What else you been signing for. Alan?

484
00:38:41.108 --> 00:38:43.110
[footsteps approach]

485
00:38:48.490 --> 00:38:50.325
Oh! The sheets!

486
00:38:55.288 --> 00:38:58.041
<i>♪♪</i>

487
00:39:02.712 --> 00:39:04.256
<i>[squeaking]</i>

488
00:39:40.250 --> 00:39:42.294
- [snap]
- [mice squeals]

489
00:39:45.964 --> 00:39:47.382
[door buzzer]

490
00:39:53.555 --> 00:39:55.264
[buzzing]

491
00:39:55.265 --> 00:39:56.391
Family?

492
00:39:59.175 --> 00:40:01.510
- Client.
- Inmate's name.

493
00:40:01.605 --> 00:40:02.813
I don't have it.

494
00:40:02.879 --> 00:40:05.563
You're a lawyer and you don't know
your client's name?

495
00:40:05.595 --> 00:40:08.149
I got a call. One of your
prisoners asked for me.

496
00:40:08.195 --> 00:40:10.238
I... didn't get all the details.

497
00:40:11.698 --> 00:40:13.408
You got a name?

498
00:40:14.951 --> 00:40:16.244
Through the opening. please.

499
00:40:19.612 --> 00:40:21.364
- Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

500
00:40:22.751 --> 00:40:24.753
I got a Henry Deaver here.

501
00:40:27.505 --> 00:40:28.964
DEPUTY WARDEN:
I'll find out who called him.

502
00:40:29.067 --> 00:40:31.059
What did Pruitt say?

503
00:40:31.176 --> 00:40:35.041
You don't get on the board by
springing problems on the board.

504
00:40:35.222 --> 00:40:38.308
My job is to fix things.

505
00:40:50.445 --> 00:40:52.696
We're moving to enterprise software.

506
00:40:52.783 --> 00:40:56.697
but the wheels turn slowly.
even in the private sector.

507
00:40:56.993 --> 00:40:59.416
I'm sorry to hear
about your predecessor.

508
00:40:59.663 --> 00:41:02.228
Always heard nice things about him.

509
00:41:02.582 --> 00:41:05.680
My. uh. father worked here.

510
00:41:06.044 --> 00:41:08.305
Visited a lot. anyway.
back in the eighties.

511
00:41:08.352 --> 00:41:11.016
- Oh. really? Corrections?
- Ecclesiastes.

512
00:41:11.125 --> 00:41:15.261
Pastor. He led Bible study
from time to time.

513
00:41:16.706 --> 00:41:18.534
Any idea why Warden Lacey would have...

514
00:41:18.597 --> 00:41:19.855
Forced buyout.

515
00:41:19.891 --> 00:41:23.628
Some folks are just not cut out
for the 19th hole.

516
00:41:24.170 --> 00:41:27.506
And some people guillotine
themselves with a Lincoln.

517
00:41:27.649 --> 00:41:29.859
Guess everybody deals
with retirement differently.

518
00:41:34.390 --> 00:41:35.573
What about...

519
00:41:37.554 --> 00:41:39.013
recent transfers?

520
00:41:39.390 --> 00:41:41.704
If he's in here...

521
00:41:41.884 --> 00:41:43.885
he's in there.

522
00:41:44.082 --> 00:41:46.501
I wish I could help you find
your client. Mr. Deaver.

523
00:41:46.560 --> 00:41:48.521
I can't very well call up a ghost.

524
00:41:50.213 --> 00:41:53.048
Thing is. a ghost called <i>me.</i>

525
00:41:53.300 --> 00:41:54.508
From inside this prison.

526
00:41:54.752 --> 00:41:56.468
Your anonymous caller.

527
00:41:56.674 --> 00:41:59.221
And then you flew two thousand miles?

528
00:41:59.264 --> 00:42:00.557
Had some free time.

529
00:42:01.599 --> 00:42:03.101
Mr. Deaver.

530
00:42:05.520 --> 00:42:09.827
The average CO is a 25-year-old
who makes nine dollars an hour.

531
00:42:09.899 --> 00:42:11.945
These guys don't think much of lawyers.

532
00:42:12.027 --> 00:42:15.023
And in a state as lily-white as Maine.

533
00:42:15.113 --> 00:42:18.533
is it possible that you were
a victim of a prank?

534
00:42:21.286 --> 00:42:23.632
If this was a goose chase.

535
00:42:24.039 --> 00:42:27.282
I hope you'll accept my apologies.

536
00:42:27.917 --> 00:42:31.923
And if you happen to find
the missing page from your book.

537
00:42:32.339 --> 00:42:33.829
you'll get in touch.

538
00:42:33.965 --> 00:42:36.216
I assume private prisons

539
00:42:36.217 --> 00:42:38.628
still fall under the purview
of the Constitution.

540
00:42:38.720 --> 00:42:40.362
This isn't Texas. Counselor.

541
00:42:40.440 --> 00:42:42.183
Actually. it would be pretty odd

542
00:42:42.229 --> 00:42:44.503
if we did have one of your clients.

543
00:42:44.642 --> 00:42:47.855
Maine got rid of
the death penalty 150 years ago.

544
00:42:48.688 --> 00:42:50.356
How'd you know I work capital cases?

545
00:42:50.421 --> 00:42:51.788
Sorry?

546
00:42:51.816 --> 00:42:54.132
I didn't say I work capital.

547
00:42:54.235 --> 00:42:57.468
Oh. we don't have gallows here.
but we do have cable news.

548
00:42:57.572 --> 00:42:59.699
I was sorry to hear about your client.

549
00:43:17.790 --> 00:43:20.466
ZALESKI: All right. that's it.
everybody. time's up.

550
00:43:20.598 --> 00:43:22.847
Get in line. better get back in.

551
00:43:26.245 --> 00:43:29.581
<i>♪♪</i>

552
00:43:29.607 --> 00:43:31.025
FEMALE GUARD: This way.

553
00:43:50.083 --> 00:43:53.461
<i>♪♪</i>

554
00:44:32.500 --> 00:44:34.497
MAN ON RADIO:
<i>Three-and one to the hitter.</i>

555
00:44:34.627 --> 00:44:35.857
MAN 2 ON RADIO: <i>He's dancin' around</i>

556
00:44:35.904 --> 00:44:37.388
<i>out there at second base a lot.</i>

557
00:44:37.450 --> 00:44:39.333
<i>He's got 'em really worried about him.</i>

558
00:44:39.372 --> 00:44:41.138
<i>but I don't think he's...</i>

559
00:44:41.217 --> 00:44:42.676
[commentary continues indistinctly]

560
00:44:42.677 --> 00:44:44.095
[sniffs]

561
00:44:49.434 --> 00:44:51.811
<i>♪♪</i>

562
00:45:03.740 --> 00:45:06.034
<i>[sportscast continues]</i>

563
00:45:15.627 --> 00:45:18.337
- [glass clinks]
- [liquid pours]

564
00:45:18.338 --> 00:45:20.715
- [thud]
- ALAN: Whistle dry?

565
00:45:23.718 --> 00:45:25.470
I'm good.

566
00:45:32.685 --> 00:45:35.081
You knew Dale Lacy a long time. right?

567
00:45:35.271 --> 00:45:36.729
The warden?

568
00:45:36.814 --> 00:45:40.135
We weren't exactly handball buddies.

569
00:45:40.276 --> 00:45:42.206
Why did he do it?

570
00:45:42.969 --> 00:45:45.971
This might surprise you.
given your line of work.

571
00:45:46.074 --> 00:45:48.475
but it's not always a happy job.

572
00:45:48.576 --> 00:45:50.569
carryin' the keys.

573
00:45:51.496 --> 00:45:53.924
I got a call from Shawshank.

574
00:45:54.502 --> 00:45:56.509
They found a kid in a cage.

575
00:45:57.377 --> 00:45:58.585
Call from who?

576
00:45:59.170 --> 00:46:00.964
I don't know yet.

577
00:46:02.423 --> 00:46:04.914
What I hear. prison's full of cells.

578
00:46:04.968 --> 00:46:07.762
Not a cell. A cage.

579
00:46:11.599 --> 00:46:13.245
Huh.

580
00:46:14.769 --> 00:46:16.437
Huh?

581
00:46:17.730 --> 00:46:19.690
[sighs]

582
00:46:19.691 --> 00:46:22.909
Henry. I'm just an old-school cop.

583
00:46:23.027 --> 00:46:26.912
Corrections?
That's a whole 'nother world.

584
00:46:27.364 --> 00:46:29.532
Whole 'nother world?

585
00:46:29.909 --> 00:46:31.244
Same blue line.

586
00:46:32.579 --> 00:46:35.330
[scoffs]

587
00:46:35.331 --> 00:46:36.499
[sighs]

588
00:46:41.350 --> 00:46:42.934
You know where he did it?

589
00:46:43.482 --> 00:46:46.702
Castle Lake. The bluff.

590
00:46:46.759 --> 00:46:49.632
Right where I found you.

591
00:46:50.263 --> 00:46:51.848
Damnedest thing.

592
00:46:53.016 --> 00:46:54.225
Huh.

593
00:46:58.104 --> 00:47:00.189
[footsteps recede]

594
00:47:09.991 --> 00:47:12.827
<i>♪♪</i>

595
00:47:26.132 --> 00:47:29.594
<i>♪♪</i>

596
00:47:41.981 --> 00:47:44.609
<i>♪♪</i>

597
00:48:09.842 --> 00:48:12.804
<i>♪♪</i>

598
00:48:25.233 --> 00:48:27.485
<i>[sportscast on radio]</i>

599
00:48:44.877 --> 00:48:47.213
<i>♪♪</i>

600
00:49:08.776 --> 00:49:11.279
<i>[sportscast continues]</i>

601
00:49:17.160 --> 00:49:18.995
<i>♪♪</i>

602
00:49:36.387 --> 00:49:38.389
<i>♪♪</i>

603
00:49:55.114 --> 00:49:57.200
- Shhh... it!
<i>- [alarm ringing]</i>

604
00:50:13.549 --> 00:50:16.511
<i>♪♪</i>

605
00:50:19.916 --> 00:50:22.078
ALAN: <i>Said it was
minus-forty last night.</i>

606
00:50:23.389 --> 00:50:26.809
<i>You know how cold that is?
Freeze to death in an hour.</i>

607
00:50:29.398 --> 00:50:31.901
<i>And you've been gone for eleven days.</i>

608
00:50:34.070 --> 00:50:36.280
<i>So what happened out there?</i>

609
00:50:47.458 --> 00:50:50.461
<i>♪♪</i>

610
00:51:11.232 --> 00:51:14.026
<i>♪♪</i>

611
00:51:17.154 --> 00:51:19.490
[water sloshing]

612
00:51:37.383 --> 00:51:39.385
<i>♪♪</i>

613
00:51:42.346 --> 00:51:43.859
When they find you...

614
00:51:44.015 --> 00:51:46.726
ask for Henry Deaver.

615
00:51:53.967 --> 00:51:57.387
Henry Matthew Deaver.

616
00:52:08.247 --> 00:52:11.000
[metallic door rolls open]

617
